    "en": "When oral anticoagulation is initiated in a patient with atrial fibrillation (AF) who is eligible for a direct oral anticoagulant (DOAC), a DOAC is recommended in preference to a vitamin K antagonist (VKA). In patients who are eligible for a DOAC, apixaban 2.5/5 mg b.i.d., dabigatran 110/150 mg b.i.d., rivaroxaban 15/20 mg o.d., or edoxaban 30/60 mg o.d. should be offered based on age, renal function and weight.\nConsider changing to DOAC. DOAC specially recommended instead of VKA when:\n- Hypersensibility or contraindication for VKA use\n- Past history of cerebral haemorrhage\n- Ischemic stroke at high risk for haemorrhagic transformation\n- AVK treatment with controlled INR ratio, and episodes of severe thromboembolic disease\n- Inability to achieve INR between 2.0 and 3.0, although good adherence to VKA treatment\n- Inability to access INR controls\n- Glomerular filtration rate &#60;30 ml/min rivaroxaban, edoxaban, or dabigatran not indicated, use VKA. Glomerular filtration rate &#60;25 ml/min apixaban not indicated, use VKA",
